<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1903-09-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1903-09-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="760" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d760">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Leishman</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1903-09-01"><hi rend="italic">September 1,
                                    1903</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Hay states that the United States war ships started for Beirut upon
                            the receipt of news of the assassination of the United States
                            viceconsul, and can not now be stopped; that they will be at Beirut the
                                <pb facs="0858" n="772" xml:id="pg_772"/> last of the present week.
                            He asks if Mr. Leishman can not have all pending questions settled
                            before their arrival, and states that he has urged this on the Turkish
                            minister in Washington.</p>
                        <p>Should the indicated arrangement be made, the war ships will make a brief
                            visit and depart whenever Mr. Leishman says they are no longer
                            needed.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>